<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-578-639  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 578 639.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  May 8 1989 v10 n19 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lessors fight government used-gear rule. (government regulationsagainst purchasing used computer equipment cost millions)(includes related article on the Computer Dealers and LessorsAssociation's claim that IBM's policy on reconfiguring oldequipment is unfair)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Altman, June.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Some computer lessors say prices for used equipment would drop andthe federal government could save hundreds of millions of dollarsif government restrictions against purchasing used computers wereloosened.andP;  The Computer Dealers and Lessors Association and someindependent lessors are fighting new regulations that make sellingused equipment to the government even more difficult.andP;  Theregulations, set forth in January, prohibit lessors from listingused equipment available for lease on the General ServiceAdministration's schedules.andP;  These schedules are essentially usedas catalogs by government agencies looking for computer equipment.andO;Less than 1 percent of the $17 billion the federal governmentspent on computer equipment in 1988 went for used equipment.andP;  Aresearch firm estimates the government could have saved $600million to $900 million by picking used equipment over new.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LeasingGovernment ContractsComputer IndustryGovernment RegulationUsed EquipmentComputer RetailingComputer Dealers and Lessors AssociationUnited States. General Services AdministrationTrade and Professional Associations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>